Introduction¶

Algorithmic Trading is a growing field which permits to replace humans (traders) by computers. It consists of implenting trading strategies into algorithms which analyses the market and take the Buy/Hold/Sell positions by themselves. Here is the future of trading and investment decision. The reasons which pop up more frequently to back this claim are the following:

- It doesn't take emotion into play
- It captures a lot of information at a time and generate a faster decision
- It identifies opportunities as it catches the micro structures of financial data

With the development of cloud solutions, increasing in the number of brockers with low trading fees, Algorithmic Trading is quickly developping today than it was in their early stages. It moved from replicating simple strategies, based mostly on trend and related to "moving average", to more sophisticated approaches driven by Machine Learning and Deep Learning.

The development of Algorithmic trading comes also with its own challenges. Monitoring the market is not an easy task as people are leaving too much power to the computer and any bug/crach can generate a big loss. Therefore, the algorithms have to be bounded by - stop loss and - take profit parameters. In other words, managing the risk is crucial while increasing the profit is the real objective.

In this theory, algorithms (strategies) follow in general the same rule which consists of the unordered sequence of the following actions:

 (1) Implementing a strategy
 (2) Optimizing the strategy
 (3) Backtesting the strategy (on historical data)
 (4) Evaluating the risk
 (5) Forward testing/paper trading (on current data)

A valid trading strategy should be one which at least beats the Buy&Hold strategy. The other criteria for chosing a strategy over the others depend on the researcher's goal. This research is considered as a primary step in quantitative research, so forward testing is out of the scope of this paper.

In this paper, we implement, optimize, backtest and evaluate the risk of four trading strategies. These are:

- Gated Unit Recurrent Neural Network (a Deep Learning algorithm)
- Small Moving Average (SMA)
- Mean Reversion (MR/Bollinger)
- A combined strategy integrating the above strategies.

Methodology¶

Our methodology is a five step process which starts with (1) constructing of the trading data from open source data, (2) Data processing (labeling and sampling process) , (3) selecting relevant features, (4) implementing the strategy, and finally (5) backtesting the strategy.

We we now move into detail for each step of our methodology.

(1) Data construction¶

(1.1) Open data

The OCHL (Open-Close-High-Low-Volume) free data comes from xxxxxxxxxxx. We add from it technical indicatiors based on: Momentum, Pattern recongnition, Statistical, Cyclical and Math tranform. We use the Talib python library to extract these features.

(1.2) Wavelet decomposition

It is generally known that the stock market is noisy. A standard moving average which is somehow central to all trading approaches as it encodes the market memory (e.g. volatility) is heavily influenced by noises and a high change in prices can still have impact after a long run period. The wavelet decomposition consists of decomposing the data into different frequencies. In this way, one can reconstruct the stock price by getting rid of the high frequency data. This is analogous to the Fourier transform, but it is particularly robust to non periodic data.

(2) Data Processing¶

(2.1) Data Labelling

We have analysed the historical data in other to find a labeling which generate a better profit. This consists of: -buying (+1) when the price will rise significantly afterward (in the 60 future periods), - selling (-1) when the price drops too much afterwards (in the 60 future periods) and hold (+0) when the price will fluctuate (in the 60 future periods).

This is a more intuitive labeling approach as it includes the rolling volatility of the returns and it stops losses as opposed to the usual (log/percent change) returns which only considers a step ahead or backward (lag=1) and does not have a market memory.

(2.2) Data sampling

The market in general does not follow the timely rule. For instance, practitioners does not trade at specific times, but under market circunstaces. In addition, data sampled on constant intervals either undervalues very active trading periods and overvalues low trading periods. One last reason and not the least is the bad statistical properties (low serial correlation, outliers, fail distribution normality tests) of time sampling stock data.

The resampling on either Volume or Ticks is particularly robust for machine learning algorithms as they needs more accurate data to build their own pattern recognition to generate trading signals. Note that the other strategies such as SMA and Mean Reversion/Bollinger are by nature built on paterns, so the timely sample data would be more accurate to find the average parameters for these later strategies. Our approach: To train the GRUNN model, we will resample the data over the volume. In other words, we will assume trading over volume rather than trading over time.

(3) Feature selection¶

Using the xgboost algorithm, we select features by level of importance.

(4) Strategy implementation¶

(4.1) The Gated Unit Recurrent Neural Network (GRUNN)

Which concepts are used? This is a Deep Learning algorithm from the familly of Recurrent Neural Network (RNN).

What is GRUNN architechture?

  • There is an input layer composed of multiple neurons, the number of neurons is determined by the size of the feature space.

  • Similarly, the number of neurons in the output layer corresponds to the output space.

  • The hidden layer(s) containing memory cells cover the main functions of the GRU networks. Changes and maintenance of cell status depend on two gates in the cell: a reset gate and an update gate. Both gates are related to two elements. One comes from the input sequence, the other is the output value of memory cells from the previous time point. Accordingly, each gate fulfills different tasks in order to achieve the purpose of filtering.

Why GRUNN?

  • It is expressly designed to avoid long-term dependency drawback;

  • It is designed to solve the common problems of vanishing and exploding gradients in traditional RNNs when learning long-term dependencies;

  • It has fewer parameters than LSTM ( Long Short Term memory ) and me train quicker or need less iteration to generalize;

  • It outperformed LSTM in most task with the exception of language processing;

How does the strategy operates?

Given the above constructed stock data as input, the model considers sequences of 5 point (the prices over the 5 previous minutes in the past) and predict a probability for each class ( Buy +1, Sell -1, Hold +0 ). A position is taken by chosing the class with the highest probability.

(4.2) The Small Moving Average (SMA) strategy

Which concepts are used? This strategy consists of considering two moving average time series built on two fixed periods(one long and one short) from the financial instrument (stock data). For instance, a short moving average could be built on a fixed time equal to 50 minutes. In that case, each point of the time series is the mean of the previous 50 minutes stock prices. On the other hand, a long moving average could be built on 200 minutes.

How does the strategy operates? When the short SMA (for instance 50 minutes SMA) crossed and go over (resp. under) the long SMA ( for instance 200 minutes SMA), then we take a buy position (resp. sell position)

(4.3) Mean Reversion (MR)/Bollinger

Which concepts are used? This strategy is also plays around the moving average concept.

How does the strategy operates? This strategy considers three moving average time series viewed as a fixed width (uniform) band. The decision to sell (-1) comes when the instrument price is above the band, the decision to buy (+1) comes when the price go under the price, and finally we hold (+0) if the price stays within the band.

In a more elaborate way, this strategy needs one moving average (the center of the band), and a width to draw the two other curves, one of each side, around the first one.

(4.4) Combined strategy

Which concepts are used?

How does the strategy operates? The combined strategy is the weighted sum of the above three strategies. The coefficients of this linear combination along with the other parameters related to SMA (moving average short and long) and MR(moving average and width) are estimated using the training data in an optimization way where the goal is clearly to maximizing the profit.

(5) Backtesting¶

Backtesting is a broad concept which simply mean searching the adequate metrics to assess the viability of a strategy and also compare strategies on historical data. There are two kind of backtesting: the vectorized backtesting and the iterative backtesting. We are performing the two in this paper in a very basic way. The whole philosophie about backtesting such as time sensitivity testing is out of the scope of this paper but are rather essential to validate a model in a very professional context. In addition, we do not take into account the trading cost (as this relates heavily to the brocker fees) and this will probably downgrade strategies with huge amount of trading.

(5.1) Vectorized backtesting

We use this approach to compare the different strategies with the Buy&Hold strategy. This relies basicaly on the closing price return and consists of taking the opposite return value each time a strategy has a contrarian position with the Buy&Hold. Thus, the vectorized backtesting outputs a time series which does not have a real/true strategy return value, but which captures the volatility (risk) of our strategy. In other words, the vectorized backtesting reveals how stable is a strategy in terms of profit and also wether a strategy beats or not the Buy&Hold strategy. By transitivity, it can permit to compare two arbitrary strategies in term of their volatility.

(5.2) Iterative backtesting

- Equity analysis

We estimate the Return of Investment (ROI) of each strategy. Namely, after each trade, we report the profit/loss and we close all the positions (sell all the stocks) at the end of the observation period. This ROI is then the return (in %) when closing our position on the market;Its mathematical formulation is given by the formula:

$$ROI= \frac{Final\_Balance - Initial\_Balance}{Initial\_Balance}$$

- Drawdown analysis

We estimate the drawdown of each strategy. This is a term that indicates the amount of money lost when trading. It is calculated by finding the difference (in %) between a relative peak in equity capital and a relative depression. This measure helps to assess the empirical strategy level of risk and its efficiency in some way.

- Maximum drawdown

To make this drawdown value less sensitive to our sample and thus more robust and scalable/more informative, we have perform a Monte Carlo simulation, based on target/label shuffling, to estimate the worst case scenario. We obtain by this process the worst drawdown that the strategy could encounter.

The main indicator that measures risk is the maximum drawdown and the intrinsic risk of our strategy can be approximated with the 95th percentile of the probability distribution of the maximum drawdown (i.e. the value of the maximum drawdown that has 5% probability of being exceeded). As in this case, using an analytical approach for such a problem can be quite difficult or even impossible. Thats the point at which Monte Carlo analysis comes in help.

The complete Monte Carlo workflow for a trading strategy is then:

                (a) Generate a sequence of N random transactions (or simply shuffling transactions)
                (b) Measure the maximum drawdown on the sequence
                (c) Repeat the previous steps M times, obtaining M different values of the maximum drawdown.
                (d) Calculate the 95th percentile of the M obtained drawdowns

The assumptions we are using are that the N transactions are independent and identically distributed and that their probability distribution is stable over time.

Comments¶

This quantitative research was a primary approach in investigating trading strategies. Some strategies appeared to be less risky than others, and some were more profitable than others. We believe that those which performed poorly such as SMA has to be improved. This can be done for instance by changing the optimization parameters or simply the used objective function.

On the other hand, the maximum drawback of strategies are relatively high.

  • This can be explained by the fact that we are evaluating the strategy during the market crash.

  • BUT, this can also be due to a non identified/adressed bias (Time period bias, Overconfidence bias, Selection bias, ...).

In other words, a couple of improvement still need to be done before moving to the next step which is "paper trading".

def optimal_strategy(parameters):
    
    # GRUNN 
    #tester=gru.GRUNN_Classifier(data.fillna(0), Features)
    #tester.test_strategy(data)
    
    # SMA
    tester1=SMA.SMABacktester(data_train.fillna(0),"ADA-USD", int(parameters[0]), int(parameters[1]))
    tester1.test_strategy(data_train.fillna(0))
    
    # Bollinger
    tester2=MeanRev.MeanRevBacktester(data_train.fillna(0),"ADA-USD", int(parameters[2]), int(parameters[3]))
    tester2.test_strategy(data_train.fillna(0))
    
    # Create comb
    comb=tester1.results.loc[:,["returns","position"]].copy()
    comb.rename(columns={"position":"position_SMA"}, inplace=True)
    comb["position_MR"]=tester2.results.position
    
    position_GRUNN=tester00.results.position
    comb=comb.drop(comb.index[[0,1,2,3,4]])
    #comb["position_GRUNN"]=tester.results.position
    
    
    # Methods
    comb["position_comb"]=np.sign(comb.position_SMA*parameters[4] + comb.position_MR*parameters[5] + position_GRUNN*parameters[6])
    
    # Backtest (Vectorized Backtesting)
    comb["strategy"]=comb["position_comb"].shift(1)*comb["returns"]
    comb.dropna(inplace=True)
    comb["creturns"]=comb.returns.cumsum().apply(np.exp)
    comb["cstrategy"]=comb.strategy.cumsum().apply(np.exp)
    
    return -comb["cstrategy"].iloc[-1] # negative absolute performance to be minimize

In [110]:
def optimal_strategy_data(parameters):
    # SMA
    tester1=SMA.SMABacktester(data_train.fillna(0),"ADA-USD", int(parameters[0]), int(parameters[1]))
    tester1.test_strategy(data_val.fillna(0))
    
    # Bollinger
    tester2=MeanRev.MeanRevBacktester(data_train.fillna(0),"ADA-USD", int(parameters[2]), int(parameters[3]))
    tester2.test_strategy(data_val.fillna(0))
    
    # Create comb
    comb=tester1.results.loc[:,["returns","position"]].copy()
    comb.rename(columns={"position":"position_SMA"}, inplace=True)
    comb["position_MR"]=tester2.results.position
    
    position_GRUNN=tester01.results.position
    comb=comb.drop(comb.index[[0,1,2,3,4]])
    
    # Methods
    comb["position_comb"]=np.sign(comb.position_SMA*parameters[4] + comb.position_MR*parameters[5] + position_GRUNN*parameters[6])
    
    # Backtest (Vectorized Backtesting)
    comb["strategy"]=comb["position_comb"].shift(1)*comb["returns"]
    comb.dropna(inplace=True)
    comb["creturns"]=comb.returns.cumsum().apply(np.exp)
    comb["cstrategy"]=comb.strategy.cumsum().apply(np.exp)
    
    return comb

Comments¶

This quantitative research was a primary approach in investigating trading strategies. Some strategies appeared to be less risky than others, and some were more profitable than others. We believe that those which performed poorly such as SMA has to be improved. This can be done for instance by changing the optimization parameters or simply the used objective function.

On the other hand, the maximum drawback of strategies are relatively high.

  • This can be explained by the fact that we are evaluating the strategy during the market crash.

  • BUT, this can also be due to a non identified/adressed bias (Time period bias, Overconfidence bias, Selection bias, ...).

In other words, a couple of improvement need to be done before moving to the next step which is "paper trading".
